import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists(): return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{source}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRIST = {
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>The narrative opens at the spring of Harod — <em>ʿên ḥărôḏ</em>, the spring of trembling — where Gideon (still called Jerubbaal) camps with his army before YHWH reduces it. As a type, Gideon at the spring of trembling is the deliverer who will save not through military size but through the God who makes armies tremble. The spring's name echoes forward to the trembling that will come on Midian (v21: 'every man's sword was against his companion'). Christ also arrives at the moment of maximum human fear and redefines what deliverance looks like.</p>",
    "2": "<p>YHWH's declaration — 'the people with you are too many for me to give the Midianites into their hand, lest Israel boast over me, saying \"my own hand has saved me\"' — is the theological heart of the Gideon narrative. Paul articulates the same principle in 1 Cor 1:29: 'so that no human being might boast in the presence of God.' God deliberately removes human sufficiency so that the glory of salvation belongs unambiguously to him. The reduction from 32,000 to 300 is an enacted theology of grace: the instrument is made so weak that only divine action can explain the result. This is the principle of the cross: Christ executed in weakness, raised in divine power.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The first dismissal — 22,000 leave, 10,000 remain — is a shadow of divine election. YHWH sifts the apparently committed from those who will actually go. The principle of the remnant — that YHWH works through a smaller faithful group within a larger nominal community — is the OT soteriology Paul applies to Israel (Isa 10:22 in Rom 9:27-29: 'though your people Israel be as the sand of the sea, only a remnant will be saved'). Christ himself said 'many are called but few are chosen' (Matt 22:14). The large call and the smaller response is not divine failure but divine design.</p>",
    "4": "<p>'The people are still too many' — a second divine reduction. The progressive winnowing (32,000 → 10,000 → 300) enacts what later theology calls irresistible grace: the elect number is decided not by human self-selection but by divine determination. The phrase 'I will test them for you there' uses <em>ṣārap</em> (to refine metal), connecting to the refining imagery of Isa 48:10 ('I have refined you, but not as silver; I have tried you in the furnace of affliction'), Zech 13:9, and 1 Pet 1:7 — testing that separates the useful from the nominal.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The water test — those who lapped versus those who kneeled — is the criterion of selection. Its theological point is that the criterion is unexpected and non-military: it is not strength, bravery, or skill that selects the three hundred but a behavioral detail at a water source. YHWH's election consistently bypasses conventional merit categories in favor of sovereign choice. The NT parallel is election itself: 'God chose what is weak in the world to shame the strong; God chose what is low and despised in the world... so that no human being might boast in the presence of God' (1 Cor 1:27-29).</p>",
    "6": "<p>Only three hundred lapped — a number vanishingly small against the Midianite 'multitude like locusts' (v12). The three hundred as YHWH's instrument against an innumerable enemy is a type of the principle in 2 Cor 12:9: 'my power is made perfect in weakness.' The inverse proportion — smallest instrument, greatest enemy — maximizes the theological clarity of the victory's source. The NT fulfillment of this type is the cross: one man's death against the entire power of sin and death, with no conventional military capacity whatsoever.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'With the three hundred who lapped I will save you, and give the Midianites into your hand' — YHWH binds salvation to the specific instrument he has chosen. The formula <em>bišlōš meʾôt ʾôšîaʿ ʾetkem</em> (with the three hundred I will save you) is election language: salvation depends on YHWH's chosen instrument, not on military capacity. The parallel with Christ is the parallel of the instrument: YHWH does not use the obvious means; he saves through what is humanly insufficient — three hundred, or a crucified carpenter from Nazareth.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The three hundred take trumpets and provisions; the rest are dismissed. Equipping the small force with the specific tools for a night mission — jars, torches, trumpets — is divine provision of exactly what is needed for the mission YHWH has planned. The theme of divine provision of precisely sufficient means anticipates the NT principle of the sufficiency of Christ's provisions: 'I will give you a mouth and wisdom which none of your adversaries will be able to contradict or resist' (Luke 21:15). The instrument is equipped for the specific plan, not for a conventional battle.</p>",
    "9": "<p>'That same night YHWH said to him: Get up, go down, for I have given it into your hand' — the nighttime divine commissioning parallels the Passover (Exod 12:29) and the events in Gethsemane, where decisive moments also unfolded at night. 'I have given it' — the perfect tense in future context is the prophetic perfect: YHWH speaks of the victory as already accomplished before a single step is taken. The divine word spoken before the battle is the basis for entering the battle. Faith acts on the word before the sight is available (Heb 11:1).</p>",
    "10": "<p>'But if you are afraid to go down, go down with Purah your servant' — YHWH's accommodation of Gideon's lingering fear by offering a companion reflects divine patience with human weakness. The offer of a companion does not change the divine word or outcome; it accommodates the weakness of the one who must act on it. Jesus similarly sends disciples two by two (Luke 10:1) rather than alone — divine mission is structured for human strength, not demanding superhuman confidence. The grace that offers Purah is the same grace that meets Thomas's doubt with extended hands (John 20:27).</p>",
    "11": "<p>Gideon overhears a Midianite soldier's dream — an enemy's unwitting testimony confirming YHWH's promise. The divine word is confirmed not through a new prophetic oracle but through overheard enemy conversation. God's encouragement of his servant comes through unexpected sources — a principle the NT affirms when opponents' speech can serve divine purposes (John 11:51: Caiaphas 'prophesied that Jesus would die for the nation'). The pagan witness to the coming victory is itself a grace for the hesitant deliverer.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The Midianites and Amalekites lying in the valley 'like locusts in abundance' with camels 'without number' — the overwhelming disproportion of the enemy compared to Gideon's three hundred is maximized here to highlight what YHWH is about to do. The locust metaphor establishes the human impossibility of the victory. The NT parallel is the cross: Christ faced the full combined power of sin, death, and darkness — the disproportion between a single crucified man and the entire power of the enemy is the ultimate expression of YHWH's pattern of saving through apparent weakness.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The dream of the barley loaf rolling into the camp and overturning the tent is a type of profound Christological significance. The barley loaf (<em>leḥem śəʿōrîm</em>) was the bread of the poor — barley was the cheapest food, in contrast to wheat. The contemptible bread destroys the military tent of the great army, typing the incarnation: the one who comes in lowliness ('he had no form or majesty that we should look at him,' Isa 53:2) overturns the stronghold of the enemy. John 6 makes the connection explicit — Jesus multiplies barley loaves and declares 'I am the bread of life.'</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Midianite soldier's interpretation — 'this is nothing other than the sword of Gideon son of Joash; God has given into his hand Midian and all the army' — is an enemy's unwitting confession that YHWH's deliverer has already won. The pagan soldier interprets his own dream against his interest. This mirrors the demonic confessions of Jesus's identity (Mark 1:24: 'I know who you are — the Holy One of God') and the unwitting confession of Caiaphas (John 11:51). Even the enemy bears witness to YHWH's chosen instrument. The adversary's testimony is the ultimate form of defeat.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Gideon worships when he hears the dream and its interpretation — the transition from fear (v10) to worship on the basis of the enemy's own unwitting testimony is a type of faith responding to divine encouragement. The past-tense announcement ('God has given into his hand') produces present worship before the battle begins. This pattern — worship as response to the assurance of victory before its enactment — is the NT pattern of faith: 'faith is the assurance of things hoped for' (Heb 11:1), and the assurance produces present worship, not merely future celebration after sight.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The tactical arrangement — trumpets, empty jars, torches inside the jars — is the instrument of the surprise victory. The jars hiding torches type the principle of 2 Cor 4:7: 'we have this treasure in jars of clay, to show that the surpassing power belongs to God and not to us.' The clay jar conceals the light until YHWH's appointed moment; the breaking of the jar releases the light. The breaking is the necessary condition for the light to appear. The type is the incarnation (divine light hidden in human flesh) and the cross (the breaking that releases redemptive light into the world).</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Watch me and do likewise' — Gideon's command is the leader's call to imitation. The principle of following the pattern of the one who leads is one of the NT's primary discipleship frameworks: 'Be imitators of me, as I am of Christ' (1 Cor 11:1); 'What you have learned and received and heard and seen in me — practice these things' (Phil 4:9). The disciples replicate not technique but obedience: they do what Gideon does because Gideon is doing what YHWH commanded. The chain of imitation runs from YHWH through the anointed leader to the community.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The battle cry 'for YHWH and for Gideon' (<em>laYHWH wəlGiḏʿôn</em>) combines the divine name with the deliverer's. This co-naming of deity and human instrument is a pattern that the NT refines: the Great Commission acts in 'the name of the Father and of the Son and of the Holy Spirit' — the triune name, with no human instrument added. The Gideon cry shows the human deliverer as YHWH's instrument while still a named co-agent; the NT moves to the instrument acting purely in the Lord's name, the instrument's own name disappearing into the one sent.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The attack at the beginning of the middle watch — just as the new watch is set — strikes at the moment of apparent security. The middle of the night, the darkness, the sudden light and sound create maximum confusion. The assault at the hour of presumed watchfulness-setting connects to the NT theme of unexpected divine action: 'you do not know on what day your Lord is coming' (Matt 24:42). The enemy who has secured himself will find himself vulnerable at the moment of apparent security — the theological law of false peace (1 Thess 5:3: 'while people are saying peace and safety, then sudden destruction comes').</p>",
    "20": "<p>'A sword for YHWH and for Gideon!' — the simultaneous trumpet-blast, jar-breaking, torch-revealing, and war-cry is YHWH's assault through unexpected instruments. The sword of YHWH is the Word of God (Eph 6:17: 'the sword of the Spirit, which is the word of God'; Rev 19:15: from Christ's mouth comes a sharp sword to strike down the nations). The battle is won by a word and a light, not by military force — the precise pattern of the gospel: 'the word of the cross is folly to those who are perishing, but to us who are being saved it is the power of God' (1 Cor 1:18).</p>",
    "21": "<p>'Every man stood in his place... and all the army ran; they cried out and fled' — the three hundred stood still while the enemy destroyed themselves. The stood-still deliverers and the self-destructing enemy is YHWH's holy war pattern: at the Red Sea, Moses said 'stand firm and see the salvation of YHWH' (Exod 14:13). The application to Christ is the cross: Jesus stood silent before Pilate (Matt 27:14) while YHWH accomplished the overthrow of the enemy through the very act of apparent defeat. The victory is accomplished not by human fighting but by YHWH's action through what appears to be passivity.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'YHWH set every man's sword against his companion and against all the army' — when YHWH acts in judgment, the forces of evil collapse on themselves. Paul makes this explicit about the powers that crucified Christ: 'none of the rulers of this age understood this, for if they had, they would not have crucified the Lord of glory' (1 Cor 2:8). The powers collaborated in their own defeat at the cross — the sword of sin and death turned against the very domain those powers sought to maintain. The Midianites' self-destruction is a type of evil's inherent self-defeating incoherence when it meets YHWH's ordained plan.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The wider tribes are called to pursue after the rout is accomplished — the pursuit comes after the victory, not as its cause. This pattern — YHWH wins the decisive battle, humans participate in the outworking — is the NT already/not-yet theology: Christ has decisively defeated sin and death at the cross (Col 2:15: 'he disarmed the rulers and authorities'), and believers now participate in the outworking of that already-accomplished victory through their own conflicts and perseverance. The pursuit of the defeated enemy is the church's mission, not the securing of a doubtful victory.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Gideon sends messengers to seize the waters — the fords of the Jordan — cutting off Midianite retreat. The strategic cutting of escape routes types the gospel's comprehensive claim: there is nowhere to flee from Christ's victory (Rom 8:38-39: nothing in all creation can separate from the love of God; conversely, nothing can escape the judgment of the one who 'holds the keys of death and Hades,' Rev 1:18). The Jordan fords as the chokepoint of escape connect baptism (entering the promised land through the Jordan) to the eschatological boundary: the defeated enemy cannot cross back into safety.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The heads of Oreb ('raven') and Zeeb ('wolf') are brought to Gideon across the Jordan — the elimination of the enemy's commanding leadership completes the chapter. As a type, the killing of the princes who commanded the oppression points forward to Christ's defeat of 'the rulers and authorities' (Col 2:15) and ultimately the destruction of death itself (1 Cor 15:26: 'the last enemy to be destroyed is death'). The presentation of the enemy's heads to the judge anticipates the Son's presentation of a defeated Satan to the Father (1 Cor 15:24-28: 'he delivers the kingdom to God the Father after destroying every rule and every authority and power').</p>"
  },
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>The Ephraimites' complaint — 'why did you not call us when you went to fight Midian?' — is the protest of those who want to share in glory after the fact. Ephraim sought honor in the victory it did not initiate. The spirit that demands inclusion in triumph without sharing in risk is the spirit the gospel exposes and transforms: 'if we endure, we will also reign with him' (2 Tim 2:12) — the co-reigning is tied to the co-enduring. Those who want the crown without the cross are precisely those to whom the cross is foolishness (1 Cor 1:23).</p>",
    "2": "<p>Gideon's diplomatic response — 'is not the gleaning of Ephraim better than the vintage of Abiezer?' — deflects honor from himself to his antagonists. The humility of the deliverer who will not defend his own honor types Christ's consistent refusal to assert his own claims (Phil 2:6-7: 'though he was in the form of God, he did not count equality with God a thing to be grasped... he humbled himself'). The gentle answer that turns away wrath (Prov 15:1) is the character of the servant-leader who absorbs complaint rather than returning it.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'God has given into your hands the princes of Midian, Oreb and Zeeb — what was I able to do compared to you?' Gideon redirects praise to YHWH and to Ephraim simultaneously. The double attribution — God gave, you accomplished more than I did — is the servant theology of the one who sees himself as an instrument rather than an agent. The anger of Ephraim subsides when they are honored. The conflict between those who worked and those who claim honor is resolved not by argument about merit but by the acknowledgment that all glory belongs to God — the finite pool of human honor disappears when divine honor fills the room.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Gideon and the three hundred pursuing while 'exhausted yet pursuing' (<em>ʿāyēp wərōḏēp</em>) — the deliverer does not stop because he is weary. The servant who continues through exhaustion types Christ who 'endured the cross, despising the shame' (Heb 12:2). The three hundred are the remnant of the remnant — reduced three times — and now they pursue while spent. Their exhaustion does not revoke the commission. 'We do not lose heart... though our outer self is wasting away, our inner self is being renewed day by day' (2 Cor 4:16) is the NT articulation of the three hundred's posture.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The request for bread at Succoth — 'please give loaves of bread to the people who follow me, for they are exhausted' — is a request for covenant solidarity: provide for YHWH's servants in their hour of need. The refusal of Succoth reflects the logic of those who commit only when victory is certain. The theme connects to Matt 25:42: 'I was hungry and you gave me no food' — the failure to provide for Christ's servants is the failure to provide for Christ. Covenant solidarity with the exhausted servants of YHWH's cause is not optional but required by the same covenant bond that creates the community.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Succoth's refusal — 'are Zebah and Zalmunna already in your hand, that we should give bread to your army?' — is faith that requires visible proof before acting. The refusal to sustain those fighting the battle before the battle's final outcome is confirmed types the response to the gospel that demands empirical certainty before commitment. This is the opposite of faith: 'faith is the assurance of things hoped for, the conviction of things not seen' (Heb 11:1). Succoth wanted the certainty of sight before giving the bread of solidarity; YHWH required the bread of solidarity before the final sight was given.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Gideon's promised discipline — thorns and briers — announces that the failure of covenant solidarity will not go unjudged. The covenant community's refusal to sustain those doing the Lord's work carries judicial weight. The specific instruments — thorns and briers — echo the curse of the ground (Gen 3:18) and may anticipate the crown of thorns through which Christ bore the curse on behalf of those who should have borne it themselves. The one who bore the thorns of covenant curse (Mark 15:17) bore them because others, like Succoth, would not bear the small thorns of covenant solidarity.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Penuel's refusal at the place whose name ('face of God') commemorates Jacob's wrestling with YHWH (Gen 32:30) is pointed irony: the city named for the vision of God refuses to sustain those doing YHWH's work. Places named for divine encounter that fail to maintain the character of the encounter they commemorate are a consistent OT theme. The church named for Christ, meeting in the name of Christ, can exhibit the same failure — receiving the name of the encounter while refusing the obligations of the encounter.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Gideon's promise to break down Penuel's tower on his return announces judgment before departure. The announcement of coming judgment before withdrawal is a type of Christ's prophetic warnings about Jerusalem (Matt 23:37-38: 'your house is left to you desolate') and the eschatological warnings of Revelation. The judge announces what justice requires before departing; the community has opportunity to reconsider before his return. The tower of Penuel that must be broken is the pride of self-sufficiency that refused to be part of YHWH's mission.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Zebah and Zalmunna at Karkor with fifteen thousand remaining — 'for 120,000 had fallen' — reveals the scope of the already-accomplished divine victory. The two surviving kings represent the final resistance after a 87% reduction of the enemy force. The theological pattern is that Christ's decisive victory at the cross (Col 2:15) leaves residual resistance to be overcome in the outworking of history — not because the victory is incomplete but because its completion is being revealed in time. The two kings who must still be taken are the last resistance of a defeated enemy.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Gideon's approach through the desert route — attacking the army 'while they felt secure' (<em>bōṭēaḥ</em>) — exploits the false security of those who believe the threat has passed. The enemy who relaxed because the main force was destroyed is caught off guard by the continuing pursuit. This types the eschatological surprise of Christ's return to those who have concluded that the battle is over and settled into presumed safety: 'while people are saying peace and safety, then sudden destruction comes' (1 Thess 5:3). The sense of security that follows a partial defeat is itself a vulnerability.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Zebah and Zalmunna fled but were captured — the commanding authority of the oppression is taken. In the Christological typology, the defeat of the kings types the defeat of 'the ruler of this world' (John 12:31: 'now will the ruler of this world be cast out') and ultimately death itself, 'the last enemy' (1 Cor 15:26). The capture is not optional — the victory is not complete until the commanding power is fully overcome. 'He must reign until he has put all his enemies under his feet' (1 Cor 15:25) is the logic of pursuing Zebah and Zalmunna even after 120,000 are dead.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Gideon returned from battle by the ascent of Heres — a transitional note marking the end of the military campaign and the beginning of the judicial phase. The victorious return of the judge types the parousia pattern: the deliverer who went out on mission comes back with captives (Eph 4:8: 'when he ascended on high he led a host of captives, and he gave gifts to men' — citing Ps 68:18, the divine warrior returning from battle). The ascent from the battle back to the settlement anticipates the ascension of Christ from the field of his cosmic battle.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The young man from Succoth writes down the names of the city's officials — seventy-seven leaders who will be held accountable. The written list serves as the evidence for judgment: those who refused solidarity are named, numbered, and confronted by name. The judgment of the named is the personal accountability that the general category conceals — not 'the people of Succoth' but these specific seventy-seven individuals who made this specific decision. The judgment at the great white throne (Rev 20:12) is similarly personal: 'books were opened... and the dead were judged by what was written in the books.'</p>",
    "15": "<p>Gideon returns to Succoth presenting the captured kings as evidence of the completed victory. The judge's return with proof confronts those who required proof before acting. The presentation of Zebah and Zalmunna to Succoth's officials is the enacted judgment: you required this sight before you would give bread; now you see it, and now comes the reckoning you delayed. The type is eschatological: at Christ's return, every act of refusal will be confronted with the evidence of his completed victory. 'Every knee will bow' (Phil 2:10) not because they are persuaded by argument but because the visible evidence is now undeniable.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Gideon disciplines Succoth's elders with thorns and briers — the fulfillment of the earlier judicial warning. The punishment is simultaneously instruction (<em>yāḏaʿ</em>, he taught them a lesson). The covenant community that refused to bear the small thorns of solidarity receives the larger thorns of discipline instead. The principle is Heb 12:11: 'for the moment all discipline seems painful rather than pleasant, but later it yields the peaceful fruit of righteousness.' But the Succoth elders do not receive discipline from a loving father — they receive it from a judge. The discipline that does not produce repentance remains as judgment.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The tower of Penuel is torn down and its men killed — a severer judgment than Succoth's. The greater the pride (the tower), the severer the judgment. The destruction of the tower connects to the Babel pattern (Gen 11:4-8): human towers built for security and prestige are brought down by YHWH's judgment. The tower that refused to support YHWH's mission becomes the evidence of its own condemnation. Christ's warning — 'everyone who exalts himself will be humbled' (Luke 18:14) — is the eschatological principle that the tower of Penuel enacts in miniature.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Gideon's question — 'what kind of men were they whom you killed at Tabor?' — reveals the personal dimension of the campaign: his brothers were killed by these kings. The kings unwittingly testify to the nobility of those they killed: 'each one resembled the son of a king.' The enemy's testimony to the dignity of the victim types the Gospel pattern: those who crucified Christ also testified to his dignity (Matt 27:54: 'truly this was the Son of God'). The recognition of the victim's worth by the killer intensifies the culpability of the killing rather than diminishing it.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'They were my brothers, the sons of my mother' — Gideon's identification with his killed brothers establishes his role as <em>gōʾēl</em> (kinsman-redeemer, the one who must avenge the family blood). The <em>gōʾēl</em> institution required the closest male relative to avenge blood (Num 35:19). Gideon as the kinsman-avenger for his brothers is a direct type of Christ as the ultimate kinsman-redeemer: 'since the children share in flesh and blood, he himself likewise partook of the same things, that through death he might destroy the one who has the power of death' (Heb 2:14). The incarnation is the act of kinship that makes Christ's redemption of humanity theologically grounded.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Gideon commands his firstborn Jether to kill the kings, but Jether is afraid and does not draw his sword. The firstborn who should be strong enough for the task is inadequate. The task falls back to Gideon himself. As a type, the firstborn who cannot execute the necessary judgment points to the only one adequate for the final judgment — the 'firstborn of all creation' (Col 1:15) who alone can execute the judgment that establishes justice and redemption simultaneously. Every human 'firstborn' is too afraid; only Christ is not.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The kings prefer to die at Gideon's hand — 'as the man is, so is his strength.' Their implicit acknowledgment of Gideon's authority in the manner of their death is a form of submission under judgment. Gideon kills them and takes the crescent moon ornaments worn by the kings — the symbols of the moon deity worship of the desert confederacy. The taking of the idolatrous symbols types Christ's disarming of the powers: 'he disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame by triumphing over them' (Col 2:15). The removal of the cultic symbols from the defeated kings is the visible evidence of the powers' defeat.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The offer of hereditary kingship — 'rule over us, you and your son and your grandson' — is Israel's attempt to institutionalize the deliverer's role in human terms. The people want to make the savior into a dynasty because they cannot conceive of salvation without a permanent visible ruler. This is the impulse behind John 6:15: 'perceiving that they were about to come and take him by force to make him king, Jesus withdrew.' The people's desire to make the deliverer a king is not wrong in its goal (YHWH's king will come) but wrong in its mechanism (human appointment of a human dynasty rather than YHWH's anointing of his chosen one).</p>",
    "23": "<p>'I will not rule over you, and my son will not rule over you; YHWH will rule over you' — Gideon's response is the theological high point of his career. The declaration that YHWH alone is king is the foundational assertion of theocracy. Samuel will repeat the same protest in 1 Sam 8:7 and YHWH will say 'they have rejected me from being king over them.' Gideon's refusal points forward to the only legitimate human king — the one who is 'YHWH our righteousness' (Jer 23:6), who reigns because he is YHWH's own king, not because the people appointed him. The throne that Gideon refused is the throne Christ will receive from the Father (Rev 3:21).</p>",
    "24": "<p>Gideon's request for the enemy's gold earrings — immediately following his refusal of the crown — reveals the gap between correct doctrine and compromised practice. Gideon correctly refuses royal status while taking the material that will fund an idolatrous object. The transition from 'YHWH will rule' (v23) to 'give me your gold' (v24) is the narrative's central irony. The man who confessed YHWH's kingship begins accumulating the instruments of a rival claim. The heart that truly renounces self-exaltation does not immediately collect the resources that enable it.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'We will surely give them' — the immediate compliance reveals that the people's devotion is to Gideon rather than to YHWH. The crowd that would have made him king now gives him their gold without hesitation. Their compliance is not covenant faithfulness but personal loyalty — they will follow wherever Gideon leads, including into apostasy. This pliability of the crowd that follows its deliverer even into error is the precise vulnerability Paul warns about: 'for the time is coming when people will not endure sound teaching, but having itching ears they will accumulate for themselves teachers to suit their own passions' (2 Tim 4:3).</p>",
    "26": "<p>The gold for the ephod totaled 1,700 shekels plus royal regalia — crescent moon symbols, pendants, purple garments, and chains from the camel-necks of the slain kings. The accumulation of royal and cultic objects means the ephod is embedded in the symbols of exactly the power Gideon claimed to refuse. He refused the crown but collected everything the crown implies. The inability to renounce glory while renouncing its title is the characteristic failure of leaders who correctly identify the principle but incompletely apply it to their own desires.</p>",
    "27": "<p>'Gideon made an ephod of it... and all Israel whored after it there, and it became a snare to Gideon and to his family.' The ephod as snare (<em>môqēš</em>) is the narrative's verdict on an instrument of worship that became an instrument of apostasy. The pattern recurs with the bronze serpent that Moses made (Num 21:8-9) which Israel later worshiped (2 Kgs 18:4: Hezekiah 'broke in pieces the bronze serpent... for until those days the people of Israel had made offerings to it'). Instruments of divine deliverance become idols when they are treated as ends rather than means. The ephod that should have pointed to YHWH became the thing pointed to.</p>",
    "28": "<p>'And Midian was subdued before Israel, and they did not lift up their head anymore. And the land had rest forty years.' The rest produced by Gideon's flawed victory is real and substantial — forty years, a full biblical generation. YHWH's deliverance through an imperfect instrument produces genuine peace. The peace of the gospel is not diminished by the imperfection of the messengers who proclaim it. But the forty years of rest will not outlast Gideon — at his death Israel returns immediately to Baal (v33), showing that the peace was personal loyalty to the deliverer rather than transformation through him. Lasting transformation requires a permanent deliverer, not a dying one.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Jerubbaal returned to dwell in his own house — the retirement of the judge to private life follows the pre-monarchic pattern. Gideon had many wives and seventy sons: the household of a man who said 'YHWH will rule over you' looks increasingly like the household of a king (cf. Deut 17:17: 'he shall not acquire many wives for himself'). The gap between confessed theology and practiced life is the Gideon narrative's sustained diagnosis of human inconsistency — the same inconsistency that makes the search for a permanent, consistent deliverer both urgent and humanly impossible.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Gideon's seventy sons — 'for he had many wives' — is the reproduction of the royal harem practice that Deut 17:17 explicitly prohibits for kings. Gideon, who refused the crown, accumulated a crown's consequences. The seventy sons will become the victims of the one son Abimelech, born of the concubine (ch9). The man who confessed that YHWH would rule planted the seed of the most explicitly anti-YHWH kingship in Judges through his accumulation of the marks of royal status he publicly refused.</p>",
    "31": "<p>His concubine in Shechem bore him Abimelech — 'my father is king.' The man who said 'I will not rule over you' named his own son 'my father is king.' The name reveals the unexamined royal self-understanding that the public theology of v23 denied. Abimelech's name is the seed of the disaster of chapter 9: the son named 'my father is king' will make himself king by killing his seventy brothers on a stone (9:5). The names we give our children reveal our actual theology more accurately than the confessions we make in moments of triumph.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Gideon died at a good old age and was buried in his father's tomb at Ophrah. 'Good old age' (<em>śêbāh ṭôḇāh</em>) honors the length and fullness of his life — the same phrase used of Abraham (Gen 25:8) and Isaac (Gen 35:29). Despite the ephod and the harem, Gideon's life ends honorably. The coexistence of genuine service and genuine failure in the same life is not unique to Gideon but is characteristic of the human condition that Christ alone transcended. Every human deliverer in Judges is simultaneously a gift and an inadequacy — pointing to the one whose life ends in both a tomb and an empty tomb.</p>",
    "33": "<p>'As soon as Gideon died, the people of Israel turned again and whored after the Baals' — the immediate return to Baal worship after the judge's death reveals that the forty years of rest was personal loyalty to Gideon, not heart transformation. The deliverer's death and the community's immediate relapse is the theological argument for why Israel needs not another judge but a new covenant: 'I will put my law within them, and I will write it on their hearts' (Jer 31:33). External deliverance produces external peace; only internal transformation produces lasting faithfulness. The judges' cycle reveals the inadequacy of human deliverers and the necessity of a permanent one who does not die — or who, having died, rises and remains.</p>",
    "34": "<p>'The people of Israel did not remember YHWH their God who had rescued them' — the failure of covenantal memory is the failure of covenant faithfulness. <em>Zākar</em> (to remember) in the covenant sense is not mere recollection but the active appropriation of past saving acts for present faithfulness. The Passover, the Lord's Supper, the Sabbath — all are institutions designed to prevent exactly this covenantal amnesia. 'Do this in remembrance of me' (Luke 22:19) is Christ's institution of the memorial against the forgetting that Judges 8:34 diagnoses. The Eucharist is the covenant memorial that sustains faithfulness in the absence of the visible deliverer.</p>",
    "35": "<p>'They did not show steadfast love (<em>ḥesed</em>) to the family of Jerubbaal in return for all the good he had done to Israel' — the final verse is a <em>ḥesed</em>-failure verdict. The people owed covenant loyalty to Gideon's house because he gave covenant service to them in their hour of need, and they withheld it. The same word for YHWH's own faithful covenant love is here applied to the human obligation of loyalty to benefactors. The final sentence of the Gideon narrative is the diagnosis that the NT will bring to eschatological completion: 'as you did it to one of the least of these my brothers, you did it to me... as you did not do it to one of the least of these, you did not do it to me' (Matt 25:40, 45).</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('christ', 'judges')
    merge_comm(c, CHRIST)
    save_comm('christ', 'judges', c)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in CHRIST.values())
    print(f'judges mkt-christ: wrote {total} verses across ch 7-8')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
